The question asks us to show that the harmonic series \(\sum_{n=1}^\infty\frac{1}{n}\) diverges. To do so, we consider the sequence \((u_n)_{n\geq 1}\) defined by \(u_n=1+\frac{1}{2}+\frac{1}{3}+\dots+\frac{1}{n}\). We want to show that \(\lim_{n\to\infty}u_n=+\infty\).

To approach this problem, we use the hint and consider the sequence \((u_{2^k})_k\) where \(u_{2^k}\) is the \(2^k\)-th partial sum of the harmonic series. Using the hint, we can show that \((u_{2^k})_k\) is unbounded, which implies that \((u_n)_n\) is also unbounded and therefore tends to infinity.

To show that \((u_{2^k})_k\) is unbounded, we first use the inequality
\[
\frac{1}{k}\geq \frac{1}{2n}
\]
for \(n+1\leq k\leq 2n\), which follows from the fact that \(k\leq 2n\). Then we have
\begin{align*}
u_{2n}-u_n
&=\sum_{k=n+1}^{2n}\frac{1}{k}
\geq \sum_{k=n+1}^{2n}\frac{1}{2n}
= \frac{n}{2n}=\frac{1}{2}.
\end{align*}
This shows that the difference between consecutive terms of the sequence \((u_n)_n\) is at least \(\frac{1}{2}\) for sufficiently large indices. Using this, we can now show that \((u_{2^k})_k\) is unbounded. We have
\begin{align*}
u_{2^k}
&=u_{2^{k-1}}+(u_{2^k}-u_{2^{k-1}})\\
&\geq u_{2^{k-1}}+\tfrac12\\
&=u_{2^{k-2}}+(u_{2^{k-1}}-u_{2^{k-2}})+\frac12\\
&\geq u_{2^{k-2}}+2\cdot \tfrac12.
\end{align*}
Continuing this pattern, we have
\[ 
u_{2^k} \geq u_1+k\cdot \tfrac12=1+\frac{k}{2}\,.
\]
Since \(\lim_{k\to\infty}(1+\frac{k}{n})=+\infty\), we conclude that \((u_{2^k})_k\) is unbounded, which implies that \((u_n)_n\) is also unbounded and therefore tends to infinity.

